<!-- INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">A display case with foggy glass or temperature problems isn't just an equipment failure — it's a sales presentation failure.</h2>

        <p>A commercial showcase refrigerator is different from every other refrigeration unit in your operation. A walk-in cooler is invisible to customers. A reach-in is behind the counter. A display case is your product's stage — customers make purchasing decisions based on what they see through that glass. Foggy glass, inconsistent temperatures that wilt fresh pastries, or failed lighting that makes your cheese selection look dim and unappetizing: these are presentation problems as much as they are refrigeration problems.</p>

        <p>In Los Angeles, this is particularly true. The city has an exceptionally strong specialty food retail culture — Beverly Hills wine and cheese shops, the Korean markets of Koreatown and Monterey Park with their extensive deli display cases, the Japanese grocery stores of Sawtelle with immaculate fresh display, the gourmet bakeries on the Westside whose entire brand is built on what you see through the glass. When a display case fails here, the commercial consequence is immediate and visible.</p>

        <p>We repair the full range of showcase refrigerators and refrigerated display cases across Los Angeles: glass-door merchandisers, open-air display cases, deli and meat cases, bakery showcases, and countertop display cases. EPA 608 certified and California C-38 licensed for refrigerant work on all systems.</p>

        <!-- ANTI-SWEAT SPOTLIGHT -->
        <div class="antisweat-block">
          <div class="as-label">🪟 Foggy Glass — The Display Case-Specific Failure</div>
          <h3>Anti-sweat heater failure: the most common showcase refrigerator complaint we see</h3>
          <p>Display cases use low-wattage electric heaters embedded in and around the door frame, glass edges, and mullions to keep the glass surface temperature slightly above the ambient dew point — preventing condensation from forming on the outside of the cold glass. When the anti-sweat heater fails, the cold glass surface drops below dew point and moisture from the ambient air condenses visibly on the glass. In LA's variable humidity — particularly during marine layer mornings in coastal neighborhoods — this failure shows up immediately.</p>
          <p>Anti-sweat heater failure does not affect product temperature and the refrigeration system may be working perfectly. But the case appears broken to customers and product is obscured by condensation. It's a $150–$280 repair in most cases. We carry anti-sweat heater assemblies for True, Turbo Air, and Beverage-Air on service vehicles.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

