<!-- CASE TYPES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Display Case Types We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every refrigerated showcase configuration in LA retail and food service</h2>

    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Glass-Door Merchandisers</h3>
        <p>Upright refrigerated cases with hinged or sliding glass doors. The most common display refrigerator in grocery, convenience, and specialty food retail. Anti-sweat heaters in door frame; LED or fluorescent lighting standard.</p>
        <div class="where">Grocery · Convenience · Specialty Food · Beverage</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Open-Air Display Merchandisers</h3>
        <p>Open-front refrigerated cases with no door — product is fully accessible. Used for high-velocity items. Refrigeration must overcome the convective load from ambient air continuously. In LA's warm ambient, this is a significant cooling challenge.</p>
        <div class="where">Supermarkets · Delis · Korean Markets · Produce</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Deli / Meat Cases</h3>
        <p>Angled-front refrigerated display for sliced meats, cheeses, and prepared foods. Often dual-temperature zones. LADPH temperature compliance critical — 41°F or below for ready-to-eat products displayed over extended periods.</p>
        <div class="where">Delis · Butchers · Korean Markets · Carnicerías</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Bakery Display Cases</h3>
        <p>Refrigerated or temperature-controlled (not always full refrigeration) display cases for pastries, cakes, and confections. Temperature precision matters for both product quality and visual appearance — humidity control is critical for glaze and fondant.</p>
        <div class="where">Bakeries · Pastry Shops · Cafes · Hotel Lobbies</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Countertop Display Cases</h3>
        <p>Compact refrigerated showcase units for countertop product display — sandwiches, beverages, desserts. Self-contained refrigeration, typically compact compressor systems. Common in cafes, coffee shops, and quick-service operations.</p>
        <div class="where">Coffee Shops · Cafes · Sandwich Shops · Hotels</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>Multi-Deck Display Cases</h3>
        <p>Wide, multi-shelf open display cases for grocery environments — dairy walls, produce cases, frozen food cases with glass doors. Large refrigeration systems with multiple evaporators. Hussmann and Hill Phoenix dominant in this category.</p>
        <div class="where">Supermarkets · Specialty Grocery · Ethnic Markets</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in LA display cases</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Foggy / Sweating Glass</h3>
        <p>Anti-sweat heater failure — the heater that prevents condensation on cold glass has failed. Distinct from a refrigeration problem: the case may be cooling perfectly while the glass fogs. LA's marine layer humidity makes this failure more visible in coastal neighborhoods. Anti-sweat heater replacement is typically a same-day repair.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Temperature Not Holding</h3>
        <p>Dirty condenser coils (fastest accumulating maintenance need in LA's dusty environment), refrigerant leak, failed evaporator fan motor, or a defrost system issue causing ice buildup on the evaporator. On open-air cases, increased ambient load from a warm store environment can push a marginally-performing system over its cooling capacity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Lighting Failure / Flickering</h3>
        <p>Failed LED driver or fluorescent ballast, burned-out LED strip, or a wiring fault to the lighting circuit. Display case lighting directly affects product appearance — dim or flickering light changes how food product looks and directly affects customer purchasing. We replace LED assemblies and can quote LED retrofits for older fluorescent systems.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Gasket Failure</h3>
        <p>On glass-door merchandisers, the door gasket provides both the air seal and part of the anti-sweat barrier around the door edge. A failed gasket allows warm, humid ambient air to enter the case continuously — raising the humidity inside the case, stressing the refrigeration system, and contributing to frost buildup on the evaporator. We carry gaskets for True, Turbo Air, and Beverage-Air.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Uneven Temperatures / Hot Spots</h3>
        <p>Blocked evaporator airflow from ice buildup (defrost system failure) or a failed evaporator fan motor creating dead zones in the case. On multi-shelf cases, a single failed evaporator fan can leave the lower shelves cold while upper shelves warm — the bottom product is fine but the top is above safe temperature.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Excessive Noise</h3>
        <p>Rattling evaporator fan bearings (the most common noise source), vibrating compressor mounts, or a loose panel or drain cover vibrating in the airflow. Display case noise is particularly disruptive in specialty retail environments — a grinding fan in a Beverly Hills cheese shop is not acceptable. Fan bearing replacement is typically a $150–$250 repair.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

